---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import headshot from "../assets/img/justin-elszasz-headshot.jpg";
---

<Layout activePage="about">
  <section class="about">
    <div class="about-inner">
      <div class="content">
        <p class="about-label">THE STORY BEHIND GOOD ENOUGH</p>
        <h1>A fellow public servant who can help</h1>

        <div class="bio">
          <p>
            During World War II, the phrase "good enough for government" meant
            that something met rigorous standards. It was a stamp of approval.
            Today, the phrase is a punchline, not a reality. It's uttered when
            something barely passes muster. The phrase has become infused with a
            sense of cynicism and resignation.
          </p>

          <p>
            Good Enough was founded to reclaim that phrase for the public
            sector.
          </p>
          <h2 class="bio-heading">About Justin</h2>
          <p>
            Justin Elszasz is a public servant, civic technologist, and maker
            with 20 years of experience in spanning engineering, public policy
            and administration, data and AI, and innovation. Previously, Justin
            served as Chief Data Officer for the City of Baltimore and Interim
            Director of the Mayor's Office of Performance & Innovation. He built
            Baltimore's first Digital Services team, launched the Baltimore Data
            Academy, and created the Data Fellows program to recruit and embed
            analysts across city agencies. Justin led the city to achieve What Works
            Cities certification, a national recognition for cities that are using 
            data and evidence to improve their services. He was nominated for the 2022 
            StateScoop LocalSmart award and was recognized by CDO Magazine as a
            Local Leading Data Executive.
          </p>
          <p>
            Justin serves on the board of directors at Open Works, the country's
            largest non-profit makerspace, and has taught graduate-level data
            visualization at the Maryland Institute College of Art. He holds an
            M.S. from Columbia University and a B.S. from Case Western Reserve
            University, both in mechanical engineering.
          </p>

          <p>
            <!--[Additional context about your approach or philosophy, if needed.]-->
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="image">
        <img src={headshot.src} alt="Justin Elszasz" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* ── About Section ── */
  .about {
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(23, 23, 23, 0.1);
  }

  .about-inner {
    max-width: 72rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 6rem 1.5rem 5rem;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr auto;
    gap: 4rem;
    align-items: start;
  }

  /* ── Content ── */
  .content {
    max-width: 48rem;
  }

  .about-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    color: var(--cobalt);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  h1 {
    font-family: "Playfair Display", Georgia, serif;
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4.5rem);
    line-height: 1.05;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .bio {
    color: var(--n700);
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .bio-heading {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .bio p {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .bio p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* ── Image ── */
  .image img {
    display: block;
    width: 220px;
    height: 220px;
    max-width: 220px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
  }

  /* ── Responsive ── */
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .about-inner {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 2.5rem;
      padding: 4rem 1.5rem;
    }

    .image {
      order: -1;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
    }

    h1 {
      font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 5vw, 2.5rem);
    }
  }
</style>
